With the optimal conditions in hand, the detection of different concentrations of DOX was investigated and the results are shown in Fig. 6
                        a. We observed that the fluorescence intensity of the NPCDs decreased continuously with increased DOX concentrations. A good linear response for the NPCDs over a concentration range of DOX of 0.5–6.5 μM was obtained, following the Stern-Volmer behavior (Fig. 6b). The correlation coefficient R2 was 0.9945 and the limit detection (LOD) was calculated to be 12 nM based on 3σ/k (where σ is the standard deviation of the blank, and k is the slope of the Stern-Volmer linear plot, S/N = 3) [22]. Compared with other detection methods [21,22,42–47], the NPCDs exhibited an excellent linear range and the lowest detection limit (Table 1
                        ). Hence, the NPCDs can be used as an effective fluorescence probe for the detection of DOX. To evaluate the selectivity of DOX, several common metal cations (Fe3+, K+, Mg2+, and Ca2+) and different biomolecules (Glc, Fru, GSH, DA, VC, Cre, UA, Trp, His, Gly, Ile, Met, Glu, Lys, Phe, Ala, Thr, Pro, Cys, Tyr, lactose, sucrose, urea, and thiourea) were investigated. Fig. 6c and d show that only DOX had an appreciable “turn-off” effect of the fluorescence intensity, indicating that the NPCDs had good selectivity for DOX.
